    <text>
    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>June 9<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1880</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I am much obliged to you for your courteous note &amp; for the gift of your ‘Spirit of Nature’.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>I will read your work as soon as I have finished a book in hand, &amp; I remain | Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway … S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi> </note>
                
            </div>
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">A copy of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_8914.xml">Baildon’s</ref> book <hi rend="italic">The spirit of nature: being a series of interpretative essays on the history of matter from the atom to the flower</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_11205.xml">Baildon 1880</ref>) is in the Darwin Library–Down. Baildon’s note has not been found.</note>
        </div>
    
